SIMPLE: owe
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Owe
<hw>Owe</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Owed</conjf> <pr>(⟦omac⟧d)</pr>, (<conjf>Ought</conjf>
<pr>(⟦add⟧t)</pr> <mark>obs.</mark>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Owing</conjf> <pr>(⟦omac⟧"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>owen</ets>, <ets>awen</ets>, <ets>aghen</ets>, to have, own, have
(to do), hence, owe, AS. <ets>⟦amac⟧gan</ets> to have; akin to G.
<ets>eigen</ets>, a., own, Icel. <ets>eiga</ets> to have, Dan.
<ets>eie</ets>, Sw. <ets>⟦aum⟧ga</ets>, Goth. <ets>⟦aacute⟧igan</ets>,
Skr. <ets>⟦imac⟧⟦cced⟧</ets>. ⟦root⟧110. Cf. <er>Ought</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>, 2d <er>Own</er>, <er>Fraught</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To possess; to have, as the rightful owner; to own.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou dost here usurp⟦br⟧
The name thou <qex>ow'st</qex> not.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have or possess, as something derived or
bestowed; to be obliged to ascribe (something to some source); to be
indebted or obliged for; <as>as, he <ex>owed</ex> his wealth to his
father; he <ex>owed</ex> his victory to his lieutenants</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O deem thy fall not <qex>owed</qex> to man's decree.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To have or be under an
obligation to restore, pay, or render (something) in return or
compensation for something received; to be indebted in the sum of;
<as>as, the subject <ex>owes</ex> allegiance; the fortunate <ex>owe</ex>
assistance to the unfortunate.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The one <qex>ought</qex> five hundred pence, and the other
fifty.</q> <rj><qau>Bible (1551).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A son <qex>owes</qex> help and honor to his father.</q>
<rj><qau>Holyday.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Owe</xex> was sometimes followed by an objective
clause introduced by the infinitive. ⟦ldquo⟧Ye <xex>owen</xex> to
incline and bow your heart.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have an obligation to (some one) on account of
something done or received; to be indebted to; <as>as, to <ex>owe</ex>
the grocer for supplies, or a laborer for services</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Owel</ent>⟦br⟧
